<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-12-08T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-12-08T13:00:00-05:00" n="418" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d418">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">123H875/198: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Phillips</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-12-08T19:00:00+01:00">December 8, 1936—7
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received December 8—4:08 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>514. My 507, December 4, 7 p.m.<note n="99" xml:id="d418fn99">Not
                                    printed.</note> and previous. I understand from the Minister of
                                Foreign Affairs that there is some difficulty in connection with the
                                visa of Hughes passport by the Italian Embassy in that it states
                                that he is assigned “to the Legation at Addis Ababa” instead of “to
                                Addis Ababa” to which latter designation the Italian authorities
                                agreed. As the objection of the Foreign Office is solely to the use
                                of the words “Legation at” on the passport itself I sincerely hope
                                that this matter may be satisfactorily arranged.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>